<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-14T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-14T19:00:00-05:00" n="136" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d136">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">847.24/768b: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Minister in Australia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-14T20:00:00-04:00">January 14, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>6. FEA is agreeable to your assuring the Australian authorities that
                                no commodities other than those listed in Exhibit A<note n="50" xml:id="d136fn50">See footnote 40, <ref target="#pg_202">p.
                                        202</ref>.</note> will be requested during the present
                                calendar year and that the dollar amounts listed are substantially
                                accurate. It has not yet been possible to determine the dollar
                                amount of requirements of hides but this is not believed to be an
                                important item.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>